chi√™ng	- {Gong} gong\n- {Gongs were found in Vietnam in the Bronze Age (ƒê√¥ng S∆°n culture from 2000 to 3500 years ago). Gongs were cast in bronze}\n- {an alloy of copper}\n- {zinc and lead. Gongs are used as a musical instrument by most ethnic groups in Vietnam. Gongs are frequently mentioned in Highland songs}\n- {and its music displays its contemplative nature. Highlanders believe that when gong music is played}\n- {there is an encounter between the human and spirit worlds}\n- {between the worlds of the living and the dead. In real life}\n- {the gong is closely associated with each stage of a lifespan. In the ceremony of blowing the ear for a newborn child}\n- {the sound of a gong serves to declare the offical acceptance of a new community member. When he or she is old enough to get married}\n- {in the ceremony of exchanging necklace}\n- {the gong seems to urge young people to dash to the battlefield and struggle for the survival of the community. If the gong sounds hilarious and fast}\n- {it heralds a victory or the ceremony of killing buffalo. When the gong sounds slow}\n- {sinister and heavy}\n- {then it is the news of a death. The gong is warm in a night of rest or around a fire with a pot of wine}\n- {an indication of a good harvest when young people gather to sing and dance and tell of their love}\n- {When the gong sounds from the communal house}\n- {it can be heard all over the mountain and forest as a call for the young men to return to the communal house. When an old man passes away}\n- {the gong echoes its farewell. Virtually}\n- {all Western Highland and Long Range tribes have their own gongs. There are various types: C·ªìng (with a nipple) and Chi√™ng (without one) and there are also different sizes depending on the tribe}\n- {each region with its own regulations. It would not be an exaggeration to say that the gong is one of the main instruments in the orchestras of the Western Highland (T√¢y Nguy√™n) and Long Range (Tr∆∞·ªùng S∆°n) tribes}\n- {used in festivals such as the welcoming of a victory}\n- {killing buffalo}\n- {forgetting a tomb}\n- {and welcoming a good harvest. There are three pieces: Juar}\n- {Trum and Vang. Juar has an accelerating tempo revealing the majestic heroism of the victory}\n- {Trum (accompanied by a shield dance) expresses the hard but brave fight of the soldiers}\n- {and Vang}\n- {with a slow tempo}\n- {tells of sorrow}\n- {grief and regret felt for fallen soldiers. Hands or sticks are used to beat the gong. Sticks can be wrapped with cloth and/or rubber and a gong can be held by hand}\n- {put on the thigh or hung on a frame when played. Researchers all agree that of all the gongs of the ethnic groups}\n- {the Ba Na gong is the most majestic}\n- {imposing} imponente\n- {romantic and echoing}\n- {the Gia Rai gong is the most solid}\n- {echoing and accelerated. c·ªëm	- {Green rice flakes}\n- {Rice growing farmers are the only ones who truly understand when it is time to gather young grains to make C·ªëm. Then young rice grains are harvested}\n- {roasted and ground down to become C·ªëm. They are put into a large firing pan under small flames and stirred slowly for a specific period of time. They are then poured into a rice mortar and slightly pounded with a wooden pestle}\n- {rythmically and at quick intervals until the husk is removed. Following this}\n- {the young rice is removed from the mortar and winnowed before being poured again into the mortar and the process repeated. This is then repeated exactly seven times so that all the husk is removed from the young sticky grains. If the pounding is done irregularly and in haste}\n- {or it is not repeated for the prescribed seven times}\n- {the green colour of the grains will disappear and be replaced by an unexpected brown colour. C·ªëm is regarded as a purely pastoral gift. To enjoy C·ªëm}\n- {it is advisable to chew it slowly so that one can feel the stickiness of the young rice and at the same time enjoy its sweet}\n- {fragrant taste. It is no exaggeration to say that the fishing rafts on AnGiang rivers are true floating villages.If you ever come to AnGiang}\n- {do not fail to visit C·ªìn Ti√™n where you can fully appreciate the poetic nature of such villages. They are made of large rafts of either bamboo or timber depending on the capabilities of the fish raisers. In most cases}\n- {they are timber rafts measuring about 12 by 5 metres and 3 metres in height. After five months -- the usual time for the fish to complete their life cycle -- the family of the fish raiser anchors the raft on some part of the Ti·ªÅn}\n- {H·∫≠u}\n- {or Ch√¢u ƒê·ªëc rivers or any major canals. C·ªìn Ti√™n actually accounts for almost half of all the fish rafts of AnGiang provinc·∫πThe two main fish species raised in cages in AnGiang are the Ba Sa and Chai which take their food from the water surface. Their food consists chiefly of rice bran mixed with vegetables such as pumpkin.A raft for rearing 50}\n- {000 Ba Sa fish needs about 3}\n- {500 kilograms of food}\n- {but for rearing 10}\n- {000 to 20}\n- {000 Chai}\n- {only 00 to 800 kilos of food are required. One raft needs only three workhands. The first harvest from a raft averages 12 tonnes of Ba Sa and three tonnes of he or Chai fish.+Net profit may account for 25 % - 30 % of the proceeds. But not everything has been plain sailing for the fish raisers of AnGiang. At its peak year}\n- {AnGiang had 1}\n- {200 rafts. In 1971}\n- {there were only 662 and the number slumped to 225 in 1980. A rapid recovery began in 1984}\n- {when the local government decreed new policies on prices and on the rearing and marketing of caged fish. Early in 1990}\n- {the AnGiang Aquatic Produce Import- Export Company loaned fish raisers three billion dong. It also found markets for caged fish in Australia}\n- {Hong Kong and Singapore. Subsequently}\n- {the number of rafts rose to 715 and fish output to 14}\n- {000 tonnes}\n- {double the figures for 1989. The expansion also provided jobs for 4}\n- {000 people. One of the biggest problems in caged fish raising in AnGiang is the supply of young fish}\n- {since most of them come from natural breeding. Production of all other fish still depends on natural breeding. Research and experimentation in this direction with regard to fish such as Ba Sa}\n- {Chai and Bong are going on at the provincial sciences committee. In recent years}\n- {caged fish raising has also been undertaken by other provinces such as H√† T√¢y}\n- {H√† B·∫Øc and Vƒ©nh Ph√∫ in the north and H·∫≠u Giang}\n- {ƒê·ªìng Th√°p and Long An in the south. Ba V√¨ district alone has 165 cages}\n- {mainly raising Indian carp. They yield from two to three tonnes of fish per cage. On average}\n- {the fish raisers get from 16 to 24 million dong in income and about seven million in net profit. Riverside villages such as Thuan My}\n- {Tay Dang}\n- {Co Do and Minh Ch√¢u are gradually shifting from fishing in the river to raising fish in cages. The administration in Ba V√¨ has made a uniform loan of one million dong to every family of fish raisers. Vietnamese restorers have found a solution by drawing upon the experience of builders in the past. A common method is either to fill hollowed-out pillars with concrete or to replace them with new ones. But both have their drawbacks. In the first case}\n- {the concrete would detach from the wood within a few years. In the latter case}\n- {the cost involved and the risk of collapse during the replacement would be high.To solve the problem}\n- {Vietnamese restorers have combined the use of traditional termite killers with the spraying of chemicals into the infested pillars. That would both kill the insects and prevent the growth of fungi. They can gnaw away each year from 0.2mm to.5mm of wood. But what is more damaging is that the humid secretion they leave on the surface will create the necessary environment for the development of fungi. This damage can be best seen at Keo Pagoda in Th√°i B√¨nh province}\n- {100 km southeast of H√† N·ªôi}\n- {where several hundred iron-wood pillars have been virtually eaten up.}

nh·∫°c c·ª•	- {Musical instrument}\n- {VIETNAMESE TRADITIONAL MUSICAL INSTRUMENTS: Vietnamese traditional instruments have a rich capacity for expression and are unique. This is shown in many ways. In general}\n- {Vietnamese traditional instruments are of simple structure. Sometimes too simple to be called instruments. For example}\n- {the leaf-horn has only two requirements: The surface of the leaf should be smooth and the leaf itself not thick. A girl holds the "horn" by the edge in her mouth and begins to produce a shrill sound. After a "performance}\n- {another flute}\n- {has only two holes - one for blowing and the other for fingering - but it can produce music written from the five-note scale. Castanets are simply two bamboo pieces}\n- {a bamboo end can become a split drum}\n- {kouniak and gourd covering is available in the garden. Further afield can be found bamboo}\n- {kouniak}\n- {wood} bosque,madera\n- {clay} arcilla\n- {leather} cuero,piel\n- {ston·∫π.. Only the parts of instruments are difficult to make. For example}\n- {with an organ the trick is to stick a reed into one end for blowing. But simple or not}\n- {these instruments are so skilfully made as to be works of art. Their sizes are also unique. Clappers can be as small as a longan kernel}\n- {a certain drum is no bigger than a lemon. Other instruments are huge. The lithophone}\n- {or Ndut Lieng Krak}\n- {is 01.7cm long and the Kh√°nh S∆°n 103cm while lithophones found in other parts of the world are only 80cm long. The Qui Dien bell}\n- {cast in 1080 in the times of Nh√† H·∫≠u L√Ω and Nh√† Tr·∫ßn}\n- {needed a 26 meter-high bell tower to house it. Another bell of the same period was cast in about 4}\n- {200 tonnes of bronze. The Van Ban bell with 180 tons in weight}\n- {made under Nh√† Tr·∫ßn}\n- {is 127cm high and has a diameter 74 cm. The bronze drum}\n- {especially the Son Dong drum}\n- {is huge}\n- {imposing and beautiful. The Thunder drum}\n- {which sounds like thunder}\n- {has a 148 cm diameter and is 170 cm high Some drums have a circumference of two metres and are made from the trunk of a banyan tree. Gongs and cymbals range from saucer-size to a plate 90cm in diameter. The different sizes mean that Vietnamese traditional instruments all carry characteristics stemming from the artistic creativity of the people.- Nevertheless}\n- {their capacity is both abundant and unique. On the ƒë√†n nguy·ªát}\n- {the musician is able to "stress" a note making it a triple-interval higher note or vice versa. The ƒë√†n d√¢y}\n- {a type of lute}\n- {also has available a "loose stress" and on the ƒë√†n b·∫ßu}\n- {monocord}\n- {a half-note}\n- {a third of a note}\n- {a quarter of a note and perhaps even less than a quarter of a note can be created. An even more subtle characteristic of the monocord is that the fingered string}\n- {touched}\n- {can produce a note lower than that made by the unfingered string. This cannot be done on any other instruments. The one-stringed monocord has a three-octave range}\n- {although some improved monocords have a four-octave range. The klongput makes sound without being touched by the musician Another technique worthy of study is that which allows musicians to play such horns as pile and xaranai to make a continuous sound without pausing or stopping. Vietnamese traditional instruments are close to the lives of the people and their activities. Vietnamese instruments - particularly primitive instruments - are part of their activities.}

It is an inviolable rule that cave visitors must not bring in a lamp}\n- {fire or any source of light.+All visitors come into the cave for the festive occasion amid complete darkness. The Th√°i men traditionally look for a pretty girl of marriageable age who must be well-built and in good health Therefore}\n- {in the cave}\n- {a boy first makes sure that he finds himself the right girl}\n- {that is}\n- {he asks in whispers after her name}\n- {her whereabouts and her parents so as not to mistake a blood sister or relative whom he cannot marry. A struggle inevitably ensues when a boy finds a girl who has a flaw and tries to get rid of her. Similar to practices such as the "moonlight dance" or "moonlight stroll" of some other ethnic minorities}\n- {when social events were virtually non-existent among the Th√°is}\n- {the Cave-Picnicking festival presented a good opportunity for young people to discover and exchange love.
